# =============================================================================
# tleap script: build alanine dipeptide (ACE-ALA-NME) and solvate in OPC water
# =============================================================================
#
# tleap is AMBER's "molecule builder". It reads force field libraries, builds
# molecules from sequences of residues, adds solvent / counter-ions, and writes
# out the topology (.parm7) + coordinate (.rst7) files that sander/pmemd need.
#
# Run this with:
#   tleap -f build.leap.in
# Output files (created in the current directory):
#   - diala.parm7   topology + force field parameters
#   - diala.rst7    initial coordinates
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Load the protein force field. ff19SB is the modern recommended choice for
# proteins in AMBER (released 2020, fits experimental backbone NMR data well).
source leaprc.protein.ff19SB

# Load the OPC water model. OPC is a 4-point water model that gives more
# accurate liquid-water properties than older 3-point models like TIP3P.
# (ff19SB was specifically parameterized to be used with OPC water.)
source leaprc.water.opc

# Build the molecule from a sequence of residue names:
#   ACE = acetyl cap (CH3-CO-) on the N-terminus
#   ALA = alanine
#   NME = N-methyl cap (-NH-CH3) on the C-terminus
# The N- and C-terminal caps stop the dipeptide from carrying a net charge,
# which makes it a clean test system for force field studies.
diala = sequence { ACE ALA NME }

# Solvate the molecule inside a truncated octahedron of OPC water,
# leaving at least 10 Å of water between the solute and the box edge.
# Truncated octahedrons use less water than cubes for the same buffer
# distance, so the simulation runs faster.
solvateoct diala OPCBOX 10.0

# Save the topology / parameter file (parm7) and the coordinate file (rst7).
# These two together fully describe the system for sander/pmemd.
saveamberparm diala diala.parm7 diala.rst7

quit
